    • map

      @Nonnull @Immutable public static <K, V> @Nonnull @Immutable Map<K,V> map(Object @Nonnull ... array)
      Returns a new immutable map of which content is added from the given array.

      Every two elements of the array form a key-value pair, that means, the array[0] and array[1] will be the first key-value pair, the array[2] and array[3] will be the second key-value pair, and so on. If the length of the array is odd and the last key cannot match the value, then the last pair will be the key-null pair to put.

      The behavior of this method is equivalent to: 

      
  return Collections.unmodifiableMap(linkedHashMap(array));
      Type Parameters:
      K - the key type
      V - the value type
      Parameters:
      array - the given array
      Returns:
      a new HashMap initialing with the given array

    • toMap

      @Nonnull @Immutable public static <K, V> @Nonnull @Immutable Map<K,V> toMap(@Nonnull @Nonnull Iterable<?> it)
      Returns a new immutable map of which content is added from the given iterable.

      Every two elements of the iterable form a key-value pair, that means, the it[0] and it[1] will be the first key-value pair, the it[2] and it[3] will be the second key-value pair, and so on. If the length of the iterable is odd and the last key cannot match the value, then the last pair will be the key-null pair to put. This is the iterable version of map(Object...).

      Type Parameters:
      K - the key type
      V - the value type
      Parameters:
      it - the given iterable
      Returns:
      a new HashMap initialing with the given iterable

    • toMap

      @Nonnull @Immutable public static <KO, VO, KN, VN> @Nonnull @Immutable Map<KN,VN> toMap(@Nonnull @Nonnull Map<KO,VO> map, @Nonnull @Nonnull Function<? super KO,? extends KN> keyMapper, @Nonnull @Nonnull Function<? super VO,? extends VN> valueMapper)
      Returns a new immutable map of which entries are put from the given map, and all key-value pairs are mapped from the old type to the new type during the put operation. The behavior is equivalent to: 
      
 return Collections.unmodifiableMap(
     map.entrySet().stream().collect(Collectors.toMap(
         entry -> keyMapper.apply(entry.getKey()),
         entry -> valueMapper.apply(entry.getValue()),
         (v1, v2) -> v2,
         LinkedHashMap::new
     ))
 );
      Type Parameters:
      KO - the old key type
      VO - the old value type
      KN - the new key type
      VN - the new value type
      Parameters:
      map - the given map
      keyMapper - the key mapper
      valueMapper - the value mapper
      Returns:
      a new immutable map of which entries are put from the given map

    • resolveChain

      @Nullable public static <T> T resolveChain(@Nonnull @Nonnull Map<?,T> map, T key, @Nonnull @Nonnull Set<T> stack)
      Resolves the final value in a chain. For example, a map contains: [A -> B, B -> C, C -> D], resolveChain(map, A, stack) will return D.

      This method gets the value with the given key by Map.get(Object), and then uses that value as the next key to get the next value. This loop continues until the get method returns null when a value is used as the key, and that value will be returned. If the given key doesn't map a value, or the loop is infinite, it will return null.

      Type Parameters:
      T - the value type
      Parameters:
      map - the given map
      key - the given key
      stack - the stack to check infinite loop
      Returns:
      the final value in a chain
